The paper deals with coded caching, which is a technique used in information theory to increase channel throughput. The paper also discusses the use of projective geometry in designing coded caching schemes. Therefore, the most likely category is cs.IT (Information Theory). The paper also discusses the application of coded caching in device-to-device (D2D) networks, which suggests cs.NI (Networking and Internet Architecture) as another likely category. The paper also involves numerical comparisons and optimization, which could fall under cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) and cs.SI (Social and Information Networks). Finally, the paper deals with improving the subpacketization of coded caching schemes, which could fall under cs.CC (Computational Complexity).
